President Joseph R. Biden Jr. has proclaimed February 26 through March 4, 2023, as National Eating Disorders Awareness Week. The proclamation highlights the prevalence of eating disorders in the United States, with nearly 1 in 10 Americans expected to develop an eating disorder in their lifetime. The proclamation emphasizes the importance of early access to treatment and support for individuals struggling with eating disorders, as well as promoting a culture of dignity and respect for all. The administration is taking action to address eating disorders through initiatives such as developing better therapies and interventions, providing tools and training for healthcare providers and community members, and investing in mental health services. The proclamation also acknowledges the role of families in caring for their loved ones with eating disorders and encourages support for those on the road to recovery. The proclamation concludes by urging citizens, government agencies, private businesses, nonprofit organizations, and other interested groups to participate in activities that increase awareness of eating disorders and improve access to care and support services.